<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" ><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="3.6.2">Jekyll</generator><link href="http://localhost:4000/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><link href="http://localhost:4000/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><updated>2018-03-11T04:27:48+09:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/</id><title type="html">rantd</title><subtitle>A personal blog for small things.</subtitle><author><name>rantd</name></author><entry><title type="html">Riemannian Geometry in Thermodynamic Fluctuation Theory</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/jekyll/update/2018/03/10/paper.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Riemannian Geometry in Thermodynamic Fluctuation Theory" /><published>2018-03-10T02:26:14+09:00</published><updated>2018-03-10T02:26:14+09:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/jekyll/update/2018/03/10/paper</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/jekyll/update/2018/03/10/paper.html">&lt;p&gt;This post is a summary about Riemannian geometry in Thermodynamic Fluctuation Theory, which is extracted from the following paper:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;code&gt;George Ruppeiner, Riemannian geometry in thermodynamic fluctuation theory, Reviews of Modern Physics, Vol. 67, No. 3, 1995
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&quot;riemannian-geometry&quot;&gt;Riemannian Geometry&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We consider a two-dimensional Riemannian geometry consisting of two elements:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;a two-dimensional manifold: a set of points parametrized smoothly by two coordinates &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;x=(x^0,x^1)&lt;/script&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;a rule for distance &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;\Delta l&lt;/script&gt; between each pair of neighboring points with coordinate differences $\Delta x^{\alpha}$, which is expressed as a quadratic form &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;(\Delta l)^2=\sum_{\mu,v=0}^1g_{\mu v}(x)\Delta x^{\mu}\Delta x^{v}&lt;/script&gt;. A manifold with a rule for distance in the previous form is called a &lt;em&gt;Riemannian manifold&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Depending on the explicit form of &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;g_{\mu v}(x)&lt;/script&gt;, we can obtain the different manifolds. For instance, if&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;% &lt;![CDATA[
g(x)=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 &amp; 0\\
0 &amp; 1
\end{pmatrix}, %]]&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;then the manifold is a Euclidean plane which has line element &lt;script type=&quot;math/tex&quot;&gt;(\Delta l)^2=(\Delta x^0)^2+(\Delta x^1)^2&lt;/script&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

